defaultIn the following, the background to what might come to be seen as a scandalous episode in the decline of BBC standards of behaviour in respect of the suppression of sceptical opinion about global warming.
defaultThe periodic nature of climate variation is 
defaultoutlined in the first two paragraphs which seek to cover, respectively, the historical background and a simplified description of the natural science and finally, some consideration is given to a possible explanation for the behaviour of politicians and me
defaultdia.
default&#xa0;
defaultPeriodic variations of climate
default&#xa0;
defaultWhen the alarm about global warming was first raised with US media, politicians should have asked a range of scientists whether the late 
default20'th
default century climate change was exceptional, whether it was likely to continue i
defaultndefinitely and whether atmospheric carbon dioxide could be responsible.  A range of views was important because the topic is clearly multi-disciplinary. They would have been assured that it was not exceptional as it was warmer still in Medieval and Roman 
defaulttimes (for example grapes were grown in Northumberland) and such periods are usually followed by much cooler conditions (dark ages and little ice age).  Furthermore changes of climate such as 2C were typically what one would normally encounter by travellin
defaultg no more than 200 miles in England.  It is too late now, of course, to ask those questions because the BBC in particular helped to ensure that they could not be asked, perhaps because the Trust and senior staff envisaged a never ending series of alarming 
defaultstories to be supplied at minimal cost to themselves by environmental activists.  Whatever the reason, the worldwide cost must now be measured in hundreds of billions of dollars.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe salient facts about climate
default&#xa0;
default1  The
default climate is periodic.  There are many
default regular cycles controlled principally by the large outer planets and the orbit of the earth around the sun.
default&#xa0;
default2  The
default long term variation (millennia) depends on the earth's orbit
default&#xa0;
default3  The
default cycle which causes significant periodic warming and cooling on a centu
defaultries scale has a period of just less than 1100 years. It was mainly responsible for the Minoan, Roman, Medieval and late 
default20'th
default century warming and it is effected jointly by Jupiter, Saturn and Uranus
default&#xa0;
default4  A
default cycle of period 178 years, also controlled by the 
defaultthree gas giants, is responsible for regular 'grand minima' when sunspot activity is minimal such as the Dalton, Maunder, 
defaultSporer
default, Wolf et al and, of course, for the one in which we now find ourselves.
default&#xa0;
default5  The Atlantic 
defaultMultidecadal
default Oscillation (period 60 ye
defaultars) and a closely related Pacific oscillation was responsible for the recent reduction of sea ice in the Arctic Ocean, for the slight warming around 1940, cooling around 1970, and, having entered the cooling phase, growth of Arctic sea ice.  It also contr
defaultibuted to the late 
default20'th
default century warming.
