defaultHerd mentality?
default&#xa0;
defaultAn explanation for the disgraceful behaviour of the BBC in the matter of their unbalanced treatment of climate change reporting lies somewhere in the inexorable separation of the two cultures 
defaultdesc
defaultribed in the book on that subject by C P Snow.
default  The fact is that the practical/scientific/technical culture should be the one that makes political/economic/media decisions on subjects such as climate change and what, if anything, to do about it.  However, 
defaultthe public school/grammar school/Oxbridge trained minds delivered to politics and the media generally, make those decisions in the belief that their background in humanities somehow gives them ability to make what they believe to be balanced judgements ste
defaultmming from wide knowledge of human behaviour and history.
default&#xa0;
defaultViewed from the other culture, their scientific ignorance, herd mentality and refusal to accept that they are out of their depth each time they speak about technical matters is astonishing.  What oc
defaultcurred was another example of 
defaultLysenkoism
default.  
defaultThis time, thanks to the BBC, an even more expensive and dangerous example.
default&#xa0;
defaultHampered by a hip problem and subsequent replacement I spent a few weeks thinking about climate and estimated, using widely available his
defaulttorical data, what I would expect the climate to be like over several millennia prior to 2000 AD and then up to 3000 AD including short term (decadal) changes in the complete absence of effects due to carbon dioxide.  I satisfied myself and many others tha
defaultt trace gases in the atmosphere must have no observable effect.  It is true that I had the advantage of a lifetime spent modelling a wide variety of complex technical problems but I was not by any means unique and very many engineers and mathematicians cou
defaultld probably have accomplished the same thing more elegantly or efficiently.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe results of such calculations appear to show that historical data are sufficient to explain climate variation without having to consider 'greenhouse' effects and thus, carbon di
defaultoxide, the very stuff on which all life depends, is not a pollutant as asserted by the Supreme Court of the United States and all of humanity stands to gain by emitting more.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe in this culture would not presume to make pronouncements or decisions about wh
defaultat lies properly in the domain of the other.  BBC staff should, perhaps, reflect on such issues and stand aside from discussion of complexities and arguments they can never hope to understand.  It is always best to stay silent lest ignorance be revealed.
default&#xa0;
defaultT
defaulthe wider problem of cultural separation is a matter requiring the attention of HMG and 
defaultit's
default ministers of education.
